<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880829-0097 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides: The Stealth Platform </HL><SO> </SO><G> EXE </G><TEXT>   Ever since the Democrats trooped home from Atlanta there has been speculation about how much of the convention's &quot;harmony&quot; resulted from Michael Dukakis's private agreement to Jesse Jackson's demands. Mr. Jackson's issue adviser, Robert Borosage of the Institute for Policy Studies, seems to think the answer is quite a lot. He told William Grieder in the latest issue of Rolling Stone, &quot;The reason we didn't have a real fight over the platform is that the Dukakis people gave us so much of what we wanted -- as long as we were willing to accept language so broad and generalized that the ideas sound innocuous. Seventy percent of the platform is actually from Jackson's agenda, but you'd never be able to figure that out unless you were an expert.&quot; </TEXT></DOC>